{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527223"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14194"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14194"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.18,0.1,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58105"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6877"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43564"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1881"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4916"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5571"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41944"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58105"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about safer drug use. He reports injecting heroin daily for the past five years. He is not currently interested in quitting but wants to reduce the risks associated with his drug use. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He reports sharing needles with his housemate occasionally and often injects alone in public toilets. He has had two non-fatal overdoses in the past year, both times when injecting alone. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are visible track marks and early signs of cellulitis at injection sites on both arms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate harm minimisation strategy to address all of this patient\u0027s immediate health risks?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supervised injecting facility","Weekly needle exchange program","Take-home naloxone kit","Rapid fentanyl test strips","Mobile outreach service"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple high-risk behaviours: needle sharing, solitary injection in public places, previous overdoses, and injection-related infections. A \u003Cstrong\u003Esupervised injecting facility\u003C/strong\u003E provides the most comprehensive approach by addressing all these risks simultaneously. These facilities provide sterile equipment, immediate medical supervision, overdose prevention and response, wound care, and safe disposal of used equipment. Staff can also provide education about safer injection practices and facilitate access to additional healthcare services.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eweekly needle exchange program\u003C/strong\u003E would help prevent blood-borne virus transmission through provision of sterile equipment but would not address the risks of solitary injection, overdose, or the need for wound care and infection management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etake-home naloxone kit\u003C/strong\u003E would help prevent fatal overdoses but requires another person to be present to administer it. Given this patient often injects alone, this strategy alone would not adequately address his overdose risk or other health concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid fentanyl test strips\u003C/strong\u003E could help identify contaminated heroin but would not address his other risk factors such as needle sharing, solitary injection, or infection risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emobile outreach service\u003C/strong\u003E could provide some harm reduction services but would not offer the immediate supervision and emergency response capability that this high-risk patient requires.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EResearch demonstrates that supervised injecting facilities prevent overdose deaths, reduce needle sharing through education and supervision, decrease public drug use, reduce ambulance calls and emergency department presentations, and provide opportunities for engagement with healthcare services. For a patient with multiple concurrent risk factors, this comprehensive approach is most appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Supervised injecting facilities provide comprehensive harm reduction by addressing overdose risk, infection prevention, and safe disposal of equipment.","Multiple risk factors including solitary injection, needle sharing, and previous overdoses should guide harm reduction strategies.","Engagement with healthcare services through supervised facilities can facilitate early intervention for injection-related complications."],"references":["Frei M. Opioid dependence-management in general practice. Australian family physician. 2010 Aug;39(8):548-52. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2010/august/opioid-dependence-management-in-general-practice"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43564"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14194"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationM